Chapter 1

Introduction

1.1 The Challenge of Predicting Chaotic Physical Systems

Chaotic dynamical systems exhibit exponential sensitivity to initial conditions, quantified by positive Lyapunov exponents. This property renders deterministic long-horizon forecasting fundamentally inadequate. The true state of knowledge about a chaotic system after finite time is not a single trajectory but a time-evolving probability distribution over physically admissible paths.

Traditional numerical integrators, even when symplectic or energy-preserving, produce a single deterministic solution. Ensemble methods such as stochastic Runge–Kutta or ensemble Kalman filters introduce randomness but typically rely on black-box integrators lacking geometric guarantees. Scientific machine learning has inherited this dichotomy: geometric neural surrogates preserve structure but remain deterministic; generative models capture distributions but violate conservation laws.

1.2 Two Parallel Paradigms in Scientific Machine Learning

Deterministic Structure-Preserving Learning. Hamiltonian Neural Networks (HNNs), Lagrangian Neural Networks (LNNs), Variational Integrator Networks (VINs), and symplectic predictive integrators embed geometric priors directly into architectures. By learning scalar potentials or discrete Lagrangians and deriving dynamics via variational principles, these methods guarantee symplectic flow and bounded energy error over long horizons. However, they produce exactly one trajectory per initial condition, ignoring the intrinsic multi-modality of chaotic attractors.

Physics-Constrained Generative Models. Diffusion models and flow matching have revolutionized distributional modeling. Recent physics-informed variants inject PDE residuals as soft penalties, apply post-hoc projections onto constraint manifolds, or enforce constraints during sampling via guidance techniques. Yet constraint enforcement remains external: soft penalties create competing gradients, while hard projections lack intrinsic geometric guarantees derived from a variational principle and may disrupt the learned distribution.

1.3 The Identified Gap

Four research streams exist, but none simultaneously provide intrinsic variational structure, full generative modeling, and action-principle grounding. Notably, Stochastic Variational Integrators (SVIs) produce stochastic trajectories but solve the forward problem given a known Hamiltonian; they do not learn a data-driven path measure. NAD, in contrast, solves the inverse/generative problem of inferring an effective stochastic action from the underlying physical structure.

