1.4 Thesis Contributions and Outline

This thesis develops the Neural Action Diffusion (NAD) framework as a mathematical and computational approach to generative structure-preserving modeling of chaotic systems. The contributions are organized as follows:

· Chapter 2 reviews the essential background: discrete variational mechanics, stochastic calculus, diffusion models, and constrained sampling methods.
· Chapter 3 presents the core mathematical foundation of Generative Variational Integrators, including the stochastic discrete Euler–Lagrange equations, the rigorous construction of the GVI probability measure on product spaces, and the weak Liouville condition.
· Chapter 4 provides rigorous theoretical analysis of distributional symplecticity under PSD, including a bound on the expected divergence via Fokker–Planck theory, and extends the path-entropy formulation to large-noise regimes using a discrete-to-continuous Freidlin–Wentzell large deviation principle.
· Chapter 5 specifies the algorithmic design: sliding-window DEL losses with mixing-based bias bounds, amortised projection networks with approximation error analysis, and numerical stability guarantees for the constrained reverse SDE.
