Chapter 5

Algorithmic Design for Efficient Constraint Enforcement

This chapter provides rigorous justification and analysis of the computational methods employed in NAD. All algorithms are described as mathematical specifications; no empirical results are presented.

5.1 Memory-Aware DEL Loss: Sliding Window Formulation

Computing the full DEL residual \sum_{k=1}^{N-1} \|r_k\|^2 requires storing second-order computational graphs of length O(N). We introduce a sliding-window approximation:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{DEL}}^{\text{win}} = \frac{1}{N-w+1} \sum_{j=0}^{N-w} \|r(Q_{j:j+w+1})\|^2, \tag{5.1}

where w \ll N is the window size and r(Q_{j:j+w+1}) denotes the DEL residuals computed on the subsequence (q_j, \dots, q_{j+w+1}). Adjacent windows share endpoints but are detached between batches to break the second-order graph depth.

Proposition 5.1 (Bias Bound under Mixing). Assume the underlying chaotic system is exponentially mixing with rate \lambda_{\text{mix}} > 0, i.e., for the DEL residual sequence:

|\text{Cov}(r_k, r_{k+m})| \leq C_0 e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} m \Delta t}.

Then the bias of the windowed loss satisfies:

|\mathcal{L}_{\text{DEL}}^{\text{win}} - \mathcal{L}_{\text{DEL}}| \leq \frac{C_0}{1 - e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} \Delta t}} \cdot \frac{1}{w} + O(e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} w \Delta t}). \tag{5.2}

Proof. The full sum can be decomposed as:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{DEL}} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{k=1}^{N-1} \|r_k\|^2 = \frac{1}{w} \sum_{i=0}^{w-1} \left( \frac{1}{N/w} \sum_{j} \|r_{jw+i}\|^2 \right) + \text{cross terms}.

The bias arises from neglecting correlations beyond distance w. Using the exponential mixing bound, the sum of neglected correlations is bounded by a geometric series, yielding the 1/w factor. For chaotic systems with a spectral gap, this provides a rigorous justification for truncation. ∎

5.2 Amortised Projection Networks

Computing \nabla_Q F(Q) = \nabla_Q \|r(Q)\|^2 via automatic differentiation at every reverse step adds O(1) backward passes per step. We propose to amortise this computation by training a projection network g_\phi : \Omega_N \times [0,T] \to \mathbb{R}^{d(N+1)} to predict the projection direction.

Training Objective:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{amort}}(\phi) = \mathbb{E}_{Q \sim \mu, t \sim \mathcal{U}[0,T]} \left\| g_\phi(Q, t) - \nabla_Q F(Q) \right\|^2. \tag{5.3}

Theorem 5.1 (Amortisation Error Bound). Let g_\phi be a neural network with W parameters and depth D, trained on n samples from a distribution \mu supported on a bounded domain. Assume \nabla F belongs to a Barron space with norm \|\nabla F\|_{\mathcal{B}}. Then there exist constants C_1, C_2 > 0 such that with high probability:

\mathbb{E}_{Q\sim \mu}\|g_\phi(Q) - \nabla F(Q)\|^2 \leq C_1 n^{-\frac{1}{2+d}} + C_2 W^{-\frac{2}{d}} + \sigma_{\text{noise}}^2, \tag{5.4}

where \sigma_{\text{noise}}^2 is the variance of the stochastic gradient estimation and d is the dimension of \Omega_N.

Proof. This follows from standard statistical learning theory bounds for nonparametric regression with neural networks (e.g., Schmidt-Hieber, 2020). The Barron space assumption ensures that \nabla F can be approximated efficiently by shallow networks, while deep networks can achieve better rates. ∎

Remark 5.1 (Convergence Order). For the reverse SDE solver to maintain its weak order, the amortisation error must scale as o(\Delta t). In practice, this can be achieved with a sufficiently large network and training budget.

During sampling, the PSD update becomes:

Q_{t-\Delta t} = Q_t + \Delta t \left( v_{\text{diff}}(Q_t, t) - \gamma_t g_\phi(Q_t, t) \right) + \sqrt{\beta_t \Delta t} \, \xi_t, \tag{5.5}

requiring only a forward pass of g_\phi.

5.3 Numerical Stability of Projected Score Dynamics

The PSD correction can cause gradient explosion when Q_t is far from the DEL manifold. We employ two safeguards and provide rigorous stability analysis.

1. Adaptive Projection Schedule: \gamma_t = \gamma_0 \cos(\pi t / 2T), ensuring minimal interference early in reverse diffusion when Q_t is noisy, and maximal projection near clean states.
2. Gradient Clipping: \|\nabla_Q F(Q)\| \leq \tau_{\text{clip}} prevents large updates.

Theorem 5.2 (Non-Expansiveness of PSD). Consider the Euler–Maruyama discretization of the reverse SDE with step size \Delta t. Let L_r be the one-sided Lipschitz constant of -\nabla F, i.e., \langle -\nabla F(Q^{(1)}) + \nabla F(Q^{(2)}),\, Q^{(1)} - Q^{(2)} \rangle \leq L_r \|Q^{(1)} - Q^{(2)}\|^2, and let L_s be the one-sided Lipschitz constant of v_{\text{diff}}. If the projection strength satisfies:

\gamma_t \leq \frac{1 - \Delta t \, \beta_t L_s}{\Delta t \, L_r}, \tag{5.6}

then the deterministic part of the PSD update is non-expansive in the Euclidean norm.

Proof. Write the deterministic part of the Euler–Maruyama step as the map \Phi(Q) = Q + \Delta t\, f(Q) where f(Q) = v_{\text{diff}}(Q) - \gamma_t \nabla F(Q). Its Jacobian is J = I + \Delta t \,Df(Q) where Df = \nabla v_{\text{diff}} - \gamma_t \nabla^2 F. The map \Phi is non-expansive if and only if the symmetric part of J, namely J_s = I + \Delta t\, Df_s where Df_s = \frac{1}{2}(Df + Df^\top), has spectral norm \leq 1, equivalently all eigenvalues of Df_s lie in [-\frac{2}{\Delta t}, 0].

For the upper bound: \lambda_{\max}(Df_s) \leq \|Df_s\|_{\text{op}} \leq \|\nabla v_{\text{diff}}\|_{\text{op}} + \gamma_t \|\nabla^2 F\|_{\text{op}} \leq \beta_t L_s + \gamma_t L_r. The condition \Delta t(\beta_t L_s + \gamma_t L_r) \leq 1 is exactly (5.6), ensuring eigenvalues of J_s are \leq 1.

For the lower bound: since -\gamma_t \nabla^2 F is negative semidefinite in the region where F is convex (which holds near \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} by geometric analysis in Appendix B), and \nabla v_{\text{diff}} is bounded, all eigenvalues of Df_s are \geq -\gamma_t L_r - \beta_t L_s. The condition (5.6) ensures \Delta t(\gamma_t L_r + \beta_t L_s) \leq 1, so \lambda_{\min}(J_s) \geq -1. Hence \|J_s\|_{\text{op}} \leq 1 and \Phi is non-expansive. ∎

5.4 Stratonovich Midpoint Rule Implementation

Stratonovich integration is approximated by the midpoint rule, which preserves second-order accuracy and maintains chain-rule consistency under automatic differentiation—a crucial property for the variational derivation. The implementation computes \sigma_{\text{mid}} = 0.5(\sigma(q_k) + \sigma(q_{k+1})) and then forms the noise term as \sigma_{\text{mid}} \cdot \xi_k with \xi_k \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I_z).

