Chapter 6

Extensions to Partial Observability and Inverse Problems

6.1 NAD with Ensemble Kalman Filtering (NAD-EnKF)

In many scenarios, the full state q_t is not observed; only a lower-dimensional measurement y_t = H q_t + \eta_t is available, with \eta_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0, R). We propose coupling NAD with the Ensemble Kalman Filter (EnKF) to perform sequential state estimation while respecting physical constraints.

Formulation. At each assimilation cycle:

1. Forecast: Generate an ensemble of M NAD trajectories \{Q^{(i)}\}_{i=1}^M from the previous analysis mean, using the PSD sampler.
2. Analysis: Update the ensemble using the EnKF analysis step:
   q_k^{a,(i)} = q_k^{f,(i)} + K_k (y_k + \eta_k^{(i)} - H q_k^{f,(i)}),
   where K_k = P_k^f H^\top (H P_k^f H^\top + R)^{-1} is the Kalman gain computed from the ensemble covariance P_k^f.
3. Propagation: Use the updated ensemble as initial conditions for the next cycle.

Proposition 6.1 (Projection-Update Equivalence). The EnKF analysis step can be interpreted as a projection onto the observational constraint manifold \{q : Hq = y\} in a suitably weighted norm. This mirrors the PSD projection onto the DEL manifold, yielding a unified constrained inference framework.

Remark 6.1 (Non-Gaussianity). The EnKF assumes Gaussianity, which may conflict with the non-Gaussian GVI measure. This can be mitigated by using iterative ensemble smoothers (IEnKS) or particle flow filters, which relax the Gaussian assumption.

6.2 Inverse Problems: Learning Stochastic Lagrangians from Data

Given observed trajectories, the underlying stochastic Lagrangian parameters \theta can be inferred by maximising the marginal likelihood:

\theta^* = \arg\max_\theta \log p_\theta(Q_{\text{obs}}) = \arg\max_\theta \left( -S_\theta(Q_{\text{obs}}) - \lambda F(Q_{\text{obs}}) - \log Z_\theta \right). \tag{6.1}

The normalising constant Z_\theta is intractable but can be estimated using Annealed Importance Sampling (AIS) or by training a separate energy-based model. Alternatively, one can employ score matching to directly learn the gradient of the log-density without estimating Z_\theta.

Potential Applications:

· Discovering effective equations of motion from molecular dynamics data.
· Inferring reduced-order models for turbulent flows.

