Chapter 7

Discussion and Conclusion

7.1 Summary of Contributions

This thesis has introduced Neural Action Diffusion, a generative variational integrator framework that bridges the gap between structure-preserving learning and distributional modeling of chaotic dynamics. The core contributions are:

· Theoretical: Rigorous formulation of the GVI measure as a Gibbs distribution on a compact product space, weak Liouville condition derived from the Fokker–Planck equation as a distributional symplecticity analogue, and a Γ-convergence proof linking the discrete GVI to a continuous-time large deviation principle (with discrete LDP proven, continuous interpretation stated informally).
· Algorithmic: Memory-efficient sliding-window DEL loss with exponential mixing bias bound, amortised projection networks with Barron-space error analysis, and stable PSD implementation with non-expansiveness guarantees derived via one-sided Lipschitz constants.
· Extensions: Coupling with EnKF for partial observability and formulation of inverse problems.

7.2 Limitations and Open Questions

1. Expectation-Only Guarantees: NAD enforces geometric consistency in expectation, not pathwise. Exact symplecticity per sample is incompatible with tractable multi-modal generation in chaotic regimes. The weak Liouville condition is the best possible distributional analogue.
2. Degenerate Noise Regularization: The Freidlin–Wentzell formulation requires pseudo-inversion of the noise covariance. The optimal ridge regularization parameter \delta remains to be characterized analytically, though Γ-convergence with joint limits provides a theoretical foundation.
3. Automatic Curvature Estimation: The Lipschitz constant L_r of the DEL residual Hessian must be estimated for stability bounds. Online curvature estimation is an open numerical problem.
4. Optimal Projection Scheduling: The cosine schedule is a heuristic. The optimal \gamma_t that minimizes DVE for a given computational budget is an open control problem, potentially solvable via Pontryagin's maximum principle.

7.3 Conclusion

NAD represents a principled step toward generative, structure-preserving uncertainty quantification in scientific machine learning. By defining a probability measure over trajectories via a stochastic discrete action principle, the framework intrinsically respects the underlying physics while capturing the multi-modality inherent in chaotic systems. The mathematical and algorithmic specifications presented in this thesis provide a complete foundation for the implementation and further theoretical development of generative variational integrators.


Appendix A

Measure‑Theoretic Foundations of the Generative Variational Integrator Measure

In this appendix we provide a rigorous construction of the probability measure p_\theta defined in Chapter 3, prove its well‑definedness, and establish weak convergence to the DEL manifold as the constraint strength \lambda \to \infty.

A.1 Preliminaries

Let \mathcal{Q} \subset \mathbb{R}^d be a compact subset of configuration space. The trajectory space for N+1 time steps is the Cartesian product

\Omega_N = \mathcal{Q}^{N+1},

equipped with the product topology. Since \mathcal{Q} is compact, \Omega_N is a compact metric space and hence a Polish space (separable, completely metrizable). We equip \Omega_N with its Borel \sigma-algebra \mathcal{B}(\Omega_N) and the Lebesgue measure dQ = dq_0 \cdots dq_N (which is finite because \Omega_N is bounded).

Definition A.1 (Deterministic Action). The expected discrete action is the function S_\theta : \Omega_N \to \mathbb{R} given by

S_\theta(Q) = \mathbb{E}_\Xi[S_\theta[Q, \Xi]] = \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} L_\theta\!\left(q_k, \frac{q_{k+1}-q_k}{\Delta t}\right),

where L_\theta : \mathcal{Q} \times \mathbb{R}^d \to \mathbb{R} is assumed continuous.

Definition A.2 (Constraint Violation). The expected squared DEL residual is

F(Q) = \mathbb{E}_\Xi[\|r(Q; \Xi)\|^2],

where r(Q; \Xi) = (r_1, \dots, r_{N-1}) \in \mathbb{R}^{d(N-1)} with r_k defined in Eq. (3.3). Because \xi_k \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I_z) and appears linearly, we have

F(Q) = \|r_{\text{det}}(Q)\|^2 + \sum_{k=1}^{N-1} \operatorname{Tr}\big(\Sigma_k(Q)\big),

where r_{\text{det}} is the deterministic DEL residual from L_\theta and \Sigma_k(Q) is the covariance matrix of the noise contribution to r_k.

Assumption A.1. L_\theta is continuous, and \sigma : \mathcal{Q} \to \mathbb{R}^{d\times z} is continuous. Consequently, S_\theta and F are continuous functions on \Omega_N.

A.2 Existence of the Gibbs Measure

Proposition A.1. Under Assumption A.1, the normalising constant

Z_\theta = \int_{\Omega_N} \exp\big(-S_\theta(Q) - \lambda F(Q)\big) \, dQ

is finite, and p_\theta(Q) = \frac{1}{Z_\theta} e^{-S_\theta(Q) - \lambda F(Q)} defines a probability measure on (\Omega_N, \mathcal{B}(\Omega_N)).

Proof. Since \Omega_N is compact and S_\theta, F are continuous, they attain finite minima. Therefore the integrand is bounded above by e^{-\min S_\theta - \lambda \min F} < \infty. Moreover, the integrand is strictly positive everywhere because the exponential is positive. The integral over a compact set of a bounded, measurable function is finite and non‑zero. Hence 0 < Z_\theta < \infty, and p_\theta is a well‑defined probability density. ∎

Proposition A.2 (Tightness). The family of measures \{p_\theta : \theta \in \Theta\}, where \Theta is a compact parameter set, is tight.

Proof. \Omega_N itself is compact, so any collection of probability measures on it is trivially tight (a single compact set \Omega_N satisfies p_\theta(\Omega_N)=1 for all \theta). ∎

A.3 Concentration on the DEL Manifold

Let \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} = \{Q \in \Omega_N : F(Q) = 0\}. In typical mechanical systems, the DEL residual vanishes exactly on a subset of trajectories that satisfy the discrete Euler–Lagrange equations. We assume the following regularity condition.

Assumption A.2. F is of class C^2 and 0 is a regular value of F, i.e., for all Q \in \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}}, the derivative DF(Q) has full rank d(N-1).

Under this assumption, \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} is a smooth embedded submanifold of \Omega_N of codimension d(N-1).

Theorem A.1 (Weak Convergence as \lambda \to \infty). For any bounded continuous function \varphi : \Omega_N \to \mathbb{R},

\lim_{\lambda \to \infty} \int_{\Omega_N} \varphi(Q) p_\theta(Q) \, dQ = \frac{\int_{\mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}}} \varphi(Q) e^{-S_\theta(Q)} \, d\mu_{\mathcal{M}}(Q)}{\int_{\mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}}} e^{-S_\theta(Q)} \, d\mu_{\mathcal{M}}(Q)},

where \mu_{\mathcal{M}} is the Riemannian volume measure on \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} induced by the Euclidean metric of \Omega_N.

Proof. This is an application of Laplace's method on manifolds (Wong, 2001, Theorem 2.1). By the coarea formula,

\int_{\Omega_N} \varphi e^{-S_\theta - \lambda F} dQ = \int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-\lambda u} \left( \int_{F^{-1}(u)} \varphi e^{-S_\theta} \frac{d\sigma_u}{\|\nabla F\|} \right) du,

where d\sigma_u is the surface measure on the level set F^{-1}(u). As \lambda \to \infty, the dominant contribution comes from u=0. A standard Watson's lemma argument gives the asymptotic expansion; the leading term yields the surface integral over \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} as stated. ∎

Thus, in the limit of infinite constraint strength, p_\theta concentrates on the manifold of physically admissible trajectories.

