Appendix B

Differential Geometry of the DEL Manifold and Curvature Bounds

This appendix characterises the geometry of the DEL constraint manifold \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} and derives explicit bounds on its extrinsic curvature, which are needed for the stability analysis of Projected Score Dynamics (Theorem 4.1).

B.1 The DEL Residual as a Differentiable Map

Define the residual map r_{\text{det}} : \Omega_N \to \mathbb{R}^{d(N-1)} by

r_{\text{det}}(Q) = \big( D_2 L_d(q_0,q_1) + D_1 L_d(q_1,q_2), \dots, D_2 L_d(q_{N-2},q_{N-1}) + D_1 L_d(q_{N-1},q_N) \big)^\top,

where L_d(q_k, q_{k+1}) = L_\theta(q_k, \frac{q_{k+1}-q_k}{\Delta t}). We assume L_\theta \in C^3.

Proposition B.1. The derivative Dr_{\text{det}}(Q) is a block tridiagonal matrix of size d(N-1) \times d(N+1) whose non‑zero blocks are

\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial r_k}{\partial q_{k-1}} &= D_{21} L_d(q_{k-1}, q_k), \\
\frac{\partial r_k}{\partial q_k}   &= D_{22} L_d(q_{k-1}, q_k) + D_{11} L_d(q_k, q_{k+1}), \\
\frac{\partial r_k}{\partial q_{k+1}} &= D_{12} L_d(q_k, q_{k+1}).
\end{aligned}

Here D_{ij} denotes the second partial derivatives of L_d.

Proof. Direct differentiation of the DEL expression. ∎

B.2 Manifold Structure

We assume 0 is a regular value of r_{\text{det}}. Then \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} = r_{\text{det}}^{-1}(0) is a smooth submanifold of dimension \dim \Omega_N - d(N-1) = d(N+1) - d(N-1) = 2d.

The tangent space at Q \in \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} is T_Q\mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} = \ker Dr_{\text{det}}(Q). The normal space is spanned by the rows of Dr_{\text{det}}(Q).

B.3 Extrinsic Curvature and the Hessian of F

Recall F(Q) = \|r_{\text{det}}(Q)\|^2 + \text{const}, where the constant comes from the noise variance. The gradient and Hessian are

\nabla F(Q) = 2 Dr_{\text{det}}(Q)^\top r_{\text{det}}(Q),

\nabla^2 F(Q) = 2 Dr_{\text{det}}(Q)^\top Dr_{\text{det}}(Q) + 2 \sum_{i=1}^{d(N-1)} r_{\text{det},i}(Q) \nabla^2 r_{\text{det},i}(Q).

On \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}}, r_{\text{det}}=0, so

\nabla^2 F|_{\mathcal{M}} = 2 Dr_{\text{det}}^\top Dr_{\text{det}}.

Lemma B.1 (Curvature Bound). Let M_2 = \sup_{Q \in \Omega_N} \|D^2 L_\theta(Q)\|_{\text{op}} be the maximum operator norm of the second derivative of L_\theta. Then the operator norm of \nabla^2 F(Q) on \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} satisfies

\|\nabla^2 F(Q)\|_{\text{op}} \leq \frac{128\, M_2^2}{\Delta t^4} \qquad \text{for all } Q \in \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}}.

This constant C_B = \frac{128 M_2^2}{\Delta t^4} is the explicit value of C used in Theorem 4.1.

Proof. On \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} we have r_{\text{det}} = 0, so \nabla^2 F|_{\mathcal{M}} = 2\, Dr_{\text{det}}^\top Dr_{\text{det}} (the second-order term vanishes). It therefore suffices to bound \|Dr_{\text{det}}\|_{\text{op}}.

From Proposition B.1, the non-zero blocks of Dr_{\text{det}} are D_{21}L_d, D_{22}L_d + D_{11}L_d, and D_{12}L_d. Since L_d(q_k, q_{k+1}) = L_\theta\!\left(q_k, \frac{q_{k+1}-q_k}{\Delta t}\right), the chain rule gives

\|D_{ij} L_d\|_{\text{op}} \leq \frac{2 M_2}{\Delta t^2}

for all index pairs (i,j), because the velocity argument introduces a factor of 1/\Delta t in each differentiation. Each row r_k of Dr_{\text{det}} has at most four such blocks (accounting for both Lagrangian evaluations at step k), giving

\|Dr_{\text{det}}\|_{\text{op}} \leq \frac{8 M_2}{\Delta t^2}.

Therefore,

\|\nabla^2 F\|_{\text{op}} = 2\|Dr_{\text{det}}^\top Dr_{\text{det}}\|_{\text{op}} \leq 2\|Dr_{\text{det}}\|_{\text{op}}^2 \leq 2 \cdot \frac{64 M_2^2}{\Delta t^4} = \frac{128 M_2^2}{\Delta t^4}.

∎

Note. The value \frac{128 M_2^2}{\Delta t^4} depends on \Delta t and diverges as \Delta t \to 0. This reflects the stiffness of the DEL constraint at fine time scales and is consistent with the stability condition (5.6), which also tightens as \Delta t \to 0.

