Appendix C

Large Deviations: Γ‑Convergence and LDP Proofs

This appendix provides the detailed proof of Theorem 4.2 (Γ‑convergence of the discrete Freidlin–Wentzell functional) and the discrete Large Deviation Principle for the GVI measure (Theorem 4.3). The continuous‑time interpretation is stated informally.

C.1 The Continuous Rate Function

Let \varphi \in H^1([0,T]; \mathbb{R}^d) be an absolutely continuous path. The Freidlin–Wentzell rate function for the SDE

dq_t = b(q_t) dt + \sqrt{\epsilon} \sigma(q_t) dW_t

is defined as

I_\epsilon[\varphi] = \frac{1}{2} \int_0^T \| \sigma(\varphi_t)^+ (\dot{\varphi}_t - b(\varphi_t)) \|^2 dt,

with the convention I_\epsilon[\varphi] = +\infty if \varphi \notin H^1 or if the integrand is not square‑integrable. Here \sigma(q)^+ is the Moore–Penrose pseudo‑inverse.

C.2 Discrete Embedding and Functionals

For N \in \mathbb{N}, let t_k = k \Delta t, \Delta t = T/N. Given a discrete trajectory Q = (q_0,\dots,q_N) \in \Omega_N, define the piecewise linear interpolation \iota_N(Q) \in C([0,T]; \mathbb{R}^d) as in Section 4.2.1. We also define the piecewise constant velocity \dot{Q}_N(t) = \frac{q_{k+1}-q_k}{\Delta t} for t \in [t_k, t_{k+1}).

The discrete rate function is

I_\theta^N(Q) = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} \left\| \sigma(q_k)^+ \left( \frac{q_{k+1}-q_k}{\Delta t} - v_\theta(q_k) \right) \right\|^2 \Delta t.

To handle the possible discontinuity of the pseudo‑inverse, we introduce the regularised version:

\sigma_\delta(q)^+ = (\sigma(q)\sigma(q)^\top + \delta I)^{-1} \sigma(q)^\top, \quad \delta > 0.

The corresponding regularised discrete functional is I_{\theta,\delta}^N(Q).

C.3 Γ‑Convergence

Definition C.1 (Γ‑convergence). A sequence of functionals J_N : X \to \mathbb{R} \cup \{+\infty\} Γ‑converges to J : X \to \mathbb{R} \cup \{+\infty\} if:

1. (Liminf inequality) For every x \in X and every sequence x_N \to x, \liminf_{N\to\infty} J_N(x_N) \ge J(x).
2. (Limsup inequality) For every x \in X, there exists a recovery sequence x_N \to x such that \limsup_{N\to\infty} J_N(x_N) \le J(x).

Theorem C.1 (Γ‑convergence). Assume \sigma is continuous and has constant rank on \mathcal{Q}. Let \delta_N \to 0 sufficiently slowly. Then the functionals I_{\theta,\delta_N}^N \circ \iota_N^{-1} Γ‑converge to I_\epsilon on C([0,T]; \mathbb{R}^d) equipped with the uniform topology.

Proof.

Liminf inequality. Let \varphi^N = \iota_N(Q^N) \to \varphi uniformly. Because \varphi is uniformly continuous on [0,T], the piecewise linear interpolants converge uniformly. For any t \in [t_k, t_{k+1}), the discrete velocity \frac{q_{k+1}-q_k}{\Delta t} approximates the weak derivative of \varphi. By lower semicontinuity of convex integrals (Ioffe, 1977),

\liminf_{N\to\infty} \int_0^T \|\sigma_\delta(\varphi^N_t)^+ (\dot{Q}_N(t) - v_\theta(\varphi^N_{t_k}))\|^2 dt \ge \int_0^T \|\sigma_\delta(\varphi_t)^+ (\dot{\varphi}_t - v_\theta(\varphi_t))\|^2 dt.

Taking \delta \to 0 and using the monotone convergence of the regularised pseudo‑inverse to the exact one (valid when the rank is constant) gives the liminf for I_\epsilon.

Limsup inequality. Let \varphi \in H^1. Define Q^N by sampling \varphi at t_k. Then \iota_N(Q^N) \to \varphi uniformly, and the discrete velocity converges strongly in L^2 to \dot{\varphi}. By continuity of the integrand and bounded convergence, I_{\theta,\delta_N}^N(Q^N) \to I_\epsilon[\varphi] as N \to \infty, \delta_N \to 0. ∎

C.4 Large Deviation Principle for the GVI Measure

Define the tilted energy \mathcal{E}_\theta(Q) = S_\theta(Q) + \lambda F(Q). The GVI measure is p_\theta^\epsilon(Q) = \frac{1}{Z_\theta^\epsilon} \exp(-\frac{1}{\epsilon} \mathcal{E}_\theta(Q)).

Theorem C.2 (Large Deviation Principle for Discrete GVI). Fix N and define the tilted energy \mathcal{E}_\theta(Q) = S_\theta(Q) + \lambda F(Q) on \Omega_N. The family of measures \{p_\theta^\epsilon\}_{\epsilon > 0}, where p_\theta^\epsilon(Q) \propto \exp\!\left(-\frac{1}{\epsilon}\mathcal{E}_\theta(Q)\right), satisfies a Large Deviation Principle on the compact space \Omega_N with speed 1/\epsilon and good rate function

J_\theta(Q) = \mathcal{E}_\theta(Q) - \min_{Q' \in \Omega_N} \mathcal{E}_\theta(Q').

Continuous-Time Interpretation (Informal). Via the Γ‑convergence result of Theorem C.1, the effective rate function for the piecewise-linear interpolations \iota_N(Q) converges, as N \to \infty with \epsilon \to 0 at a compatible rate, to the tilted continuous rate function

\Lambda_\theta[\varphi] = I_\epsilon[\varphi] + \lambda \int_0^T \|r(\varphi(t))\|^2\, dt.

A rigorous joint LDP in path space requires specifying the relative rates of N \to \infty and \epsilon \to 0; we state the discrete result as the primary claim and leave the joint‑limit analysis to future work.

Proof of Theorem C.2. Since \Omega_N is compact and \mathcal{E}_\theta is continuous, this is a direct consequence of Varadhan's lemma for Gibbs measures on compact metric spaces (Dembo & Zeitouni, 1998, Theorem 4.3.1). The rate function is simply the energy shifted by its minimum, which is attained by compactness. Goodness (i.e., compact sublevel sets) is automatic on a compact space. ∎

