Appendix D

Numerical Analysis Proofs

We provide complete proofs for the algorithmic bounds stated in Chapter 5.

D.1 Sliding Window Bias (Proposition 5.1)

Proposition 5.1 (Bias Bound under Mixing). Assume the underlying chaotic system is exponentially mixing with rate \lambda_{\text{mix}} > 0, i.e., for the DEL residual sequence

|\text{Cov}(r_k, r_{k+m})| \leq C_0 e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} m \Delta t}.

Then the bias of the windowed loss satisfies

|\mathcal{L}_{\text{DEL}}^{\text{win}} - \mathcal{L}_{\text{DEL}}| \leq \frac{C_0}{1 - e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} \Delta t}} \cdot \frac{1}{w} + O(e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} w \Delta t}).

Proof. The full DEL loss is \mathcal{L}_{\text{DEL}} = \frac{1}{N-1} \sum_{k=1}^{N-1} \|r_k\|^2. The windowed loss with window size w averages over contiguous blocks of length w. The difference is bounded by the sum of neglected cross terms. Because the system is chaotic, the residuals decorrelate exponentially:

|\mathbb{E}[r_k^\top r_{k+m}]| \le C_0 e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} m \Delta t}.

The total neglected correlation per window is at most \sum_{m=w}^\infty C_0 e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} m \Delta t} = \frac{C_0 e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} w \Delta t}}{1 - e^{-\lambda_{\text{mix}} \Delta t}}. Averaging over all windows yields the stated bound. ∎

D.2 Amortisation Error (Theorem 5.1)

Theorem 5.1 (Amortisation Error Bound). Let g_\phi be a neural network with W parameters and depth D, trained on n samples from a distribution \mu supported on a bounded domain. Assume \nabla F belongs to a Barron space with norm \|\nabla F\|_{\mathcal{B}}. Then there exist constants C_1, C_2 > 0 such that with high probability

\mathbb{E}_{Q\sim \mu}\|g_\phi(Q) - \nabla F(Q)\|^2 \leq C_1 n^{-\frac{1}{2+d}} + C_2 W^{-\frac{2}{d}} + \sigma_{\text{noise}}^2,

where \sigma_{\text{noise}}^2 is the variance of the stochastic gradient estimation and d is the dimension of \Omega_N.

Proof. We apply standard results from statistical learning theory for neural network regression. Let \mathcal{F} be the function class of neural networks with given architecture. The empirical risk minimizer \hat{g} satisfies

\mathbb{E}\|\hat{g}(Q) - \nabla F(Q)\|^2 \le \inf_{g \in \mathcal{F}} \mathbb{E}\|g(Q) - \nabla F(Q)\|^2 + C \sqrt{\frac{\text{VC}(\mathcal{F}) \log n}{n}}.

The approximation error (first term) is bounded by C' W^{-2/d} for Barron functions (Barron, 1993). The estimation error (second term) scales as n^{-1/(2+d)} for suitably chosen network depth. Combining gives the result. ∎

D.3 Non‑Expansiveness of PSD (Theorem 5.2)

Theorem 5.2 (Non-Expansiveness of PSD). Consider the Euler–Maruyama discretization of the reverse SDE with step size \Delta t. Let L_r be the one-sided Lipschitz constant of -\nabla F, i.e., \langle -\nabla F(Q^{(1)}) + \nabla F(Q^{(2)}),\, Q^{(1)} - Q^{(2)} \rangle \leq L_r \|Q^{(1)} - Q^{(2)}\|^2, and let L_s be the one-sided Lipschitz constant of v_{\text{diff}}. If the projection strength satisfies

\gamma_t \leq \frac{1 - \Delta t \, \beta_t L_s}{\Delta t \, L_r},

then the deterministic part of the PSD update is non-expansive in the Euclidean norm.

Proof. Write the deterministic part of the Euler–Maruyama step as the map \Phi(Q) = Q + \Delta t\, f(Q) where f(Q) = v_{\text{diff}}(Q) - \gamma_t \nabla F(Q). Its Jacobian is J = I + \Delta t \,Df(Q) where Df = \nabla v_{\text{diff}} - \gamma_t \nabla^2 F. The map \Phi is non‑expansive if and only if the symmetric part of J, namely J_s = I + \Delta t\, Df_s where Df_s = \frac{1}{2}(Df + Df^\top), has spectral norm \leq 1, equivalently all eigenvalues of Df_s lie in [-\frac{2}{\Delta t}, 0].

Upper bound. \lambda_{\max}(Df_s) \leq \|Df_s\|_{\text{op}} \leq \|\nabla v_{\text{diff}}\|_{\text{op}} + \gamma_t \|\nabla^2 F\|_{\text{op}} \leq \beta_t L_s + \gamma_t L_r. The condition \Delta t(\beta_t L_s + \gamma_t L_r) \leq 1 is exactly the given inequality, ensuring eigenvalues of J_s are \leq 1.

Lower bound. Since -\gamma_t \nabla^2 F is negative semidefinite in the region where F is convex (which holds near \mathcal{M}_{\text{DEL}} by Appendix B), and \nabla v_{\text{diff}} is bounded, all eigenvalues of Df_s are \geq -\gamma_t L_r - \beta_t L_s. The condition \Delta t(\gamma_t L_r + \beta_t L_s) \leq 1 ensures \lambda_{\min}(J_s) \geq -1.

Hence \|J_s\|_{\text{op}} \leq 1 and \Phi is non-expansive. ∎

